<section class="section">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">01 · Cleveland Range in the SoCal commercial steam market</p>
    <h2>The American steam-equipment specialty since 1932.</h2>

    <p>Cleveland Range is the American commercial steam equipment manufacturer founded in 1932 in Cleveland, Ohio. The brand has specialized in steam-jacketed kettles, direct-steam kettles, and convection steamers (SteamCraft line, covered separately on the steamer-repair side) for over 90 years. Welbilt acquired Cleveland Range in 2008; Ali Group acquired Welbilt in 2022, making Ali Group the ultimate corporate parent. Sister brands within Welbilt include Garland, Frymaster, Pitco, Manitowoc Ice, Lincoln Foodservice, Convotherm, Delfield, and Wells. At Ali Group level, Cleveland Range shares ownership with Beverage-Air, Scotsman, Ice-O-Matic, and Champion.</p>

    <p>Across SoCal, Cleveland Range steam-jacketed kettles are common in: institutional kitchens (LAUSD, UC and CSU campus dining, hospital cafeterias, healthcare meal services), large catering operations, banquet kitchens at hotels and event venues, and high-volume restaurants with soup, stew, sauce, or stock production. The KGL gas-fired kettles in 25-80 gallon sizes are the most common in our service calls. Electric KEL kettles appear more in urban kitchens with restricted gas access. Direct-steam KDL units appear in larger institutional kitchens connected to a central building boiler.</p>

    <p>$120 commercial diagnostic, applied to repair. Same-day response across LA, OC, Ventura. Next-day for Riverside and San Bernardino. Phones answered 24/7. Parent: <a href="/commercial/kettle-repair/">commercial kettle repair</a>.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section section-gray">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">02 · Cleveland Range kettle product lines</p>
    <h2>Series and common service items.</h2>

    <h3 class="brand-h3">KGL Series, Gas-Fired Steam Jacketed</h3>
    <p>KGL-25, KGL-40, KGL-60, KGL-80, KGL-100 (gallon capacity). Self-contained gas-fired steam jacket: the kettle generates its own steam from sealed water charge in the jacket, no building boiler required. Pilot or electronic ignition fires the burner that heats the jacket water; pressure rises to 15-50 psig depending on model and produces cooking heat through the jacket. Common service items: thermopile (year 4-7, $260-440), gas valve (year 8-12, $480-720), pressure relief valve (annual inspection, replace as needed $280-440), water-level sight glass (cleaning + replacement $200-340), pilot orifice cleaning $200-280.</p>

    <h3 class="brand-h3">KEL Series, Electric Steam Jacketed</h3>
    <p>KEL-25, KEL-40, KEL-60, KEL-80. Electric heating elements heat the jacket water rather than gas burner. Common service items: heating element replacement (year 6-10, $640-920), contactor or relay failure ($340-540), pressure relief valve service, jacket water-level control. Smaller footprint than KGL gas units, common in urban kitchens with limited gas service.</p>

    <h3 class="brand-h3">KDL Series, Direct-Steam Connection</h3>
    <p>Direct-steam kettles connect to a central building boiler system rather than self-generating steam. Used in institutional kitchens with central boilers (large hospital systems, university dining, large hotels). Common service items: steam supply valve, condensate trap, jacket inlet/outlet fittings, plus the pressure relief valve common to all jacketed kettle architecture. The diagnostic considers both the kettle itself and the steam supply system upstream.</p>

    <h3 class="brand-h3">MKDL Mixer-Kettle and Specialty</h3>
    <p>Combination mixer-kettle units add a paddle drive for continuous stirring during cooking. Common in commercial soup, sauce, and stew production. Service includes the kettle architecture above plus the mixer drive motor, gear reducer, and shaft seal. Tilt-Kettle series adds manual or motorized tilt for emptying. SE tabletop steam kettle is the smallest unit, common in small-volume operations.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">03 · Common scenarios</p>
    <h2>Top Cleveland Range kettle repairs in our 5-county territory.</h2>
    <ol class="num-list">
      <li><strong>Pilot won't stay lit on KGL gas units (year 4-7).</strong> Thermopile failure most common. $260-440 all-in.</li>
      <li><strong>Pressure relief valve replacement.</strong> Annual safety inspection per CA Title 8; replace when valve weeps or fails to test cleanly. $280-440.</li>
      <li><strong>Heating element on KEL electric units (year 6-10).</strong> $640-920 typical.</li>
      <li><strong>Sight glass cleaning or replacement.</strong> Mineral scale buildup obscures the water-level reading. $200-340.</li>
      <li><strong>Gas valve replacement on KGL (year 8-12).</strong> $480-720 all-in.</li>
      <li><strong>Mixer drive motor or seal on MKDL.</strong> $480-820 typical.</li>
      <li><strong>Tilt mechanism service (manual or motorized).</strong> $340-540 depending on unit size.</li>
    </ol>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section section-gray">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">04 · Real Cleveland Range repairs</p>
    <h2>Composite stories from the route.</h2>
    <div class="story-grid">
      <div class="story-card">
        <h3>LAUSD high school cafeteria, KGL-60 gas-fired (year 8)</h3>
        <p>Pilot wouldn't stay lit before breakfast prep. Diagnosed thermopile failure: millivolt output 180 mV (needs 250+ at the gas valve). Replaced thermopile with OEM Cleveland Range part. Tested pilot stability through full burner cycle. Total: $120 plus $340 part plus 75 minutes labor = $560.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="story-card">
        <h3>Pasadena catering kitchen, KEL-40 electric (year 9)</h3>
        <p>Kettle not heating, water in jacket cold. Element continuity test: open circuit on one of the two heating elements. Replaced element. Tested under load 45 minutes, jacket pressure recovery normal. Total: $120 plus $740 part plus 90 minutes labor = $980.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="story-card">
        <h3>Cedars-Sinai cafeteria, MKDL-60 mixer-kettle (year 11)</h3>
        <p>Mixer paddle stopped during soup production. Diagnosed mixer drive motor seizure. Replaced motor and shaft seal in single visit. Tested mixer cycle through 30 minutes of run time. HACCP temperature documentation provided for the institutional record. Total: $120 plus $620 parts plus 120 minutes labor = $980.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="story-card">
        <h3>Marina del Rey hotel banquet kitchen, KGL-80 (year 12)</h3>
        <p>Annual pressure relief valve inspection found the valve weeping. Replaced relief valve with OEM Cleveland Range spec. Provided inspection documentation appropriate for the hotel's mechanical maintenance file. Total: $120 plus $360 part plus 45 minutes labor = $525.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">05 · Honest scope</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">What we do for Cleveland Range, and what we don't.</h2>
    <p><strong>We service:</strong> all Cleveland Range kettle product lines (KGL gas-fired, KEL electric, KDL direct-steam, MKDL mixer-kettle, SE tabletop, Tilt-Kettle series), thermopile and gas valve service, electric element and contactor service, pressure relief valve replacement and annual inspection documentation, mixer drive motor and seal service, tilt mechanism service, sight glass cleaning and replacement, water-level control service.</p>
    <p><strong>We don't do:</strong> central building boiler repair (separate licensed boiler trade for KDL kettles connected to building steam supply), boiler permit work that requires CA boiler-licensed specialty contractor authorization, custom kettle fabrication. For boiler-permit-specific questions consult your facility's mechanical engineer or a boiler-licensed contractor.</p>
  </div>
</section>

